This is a known breaking change. Android deprecated `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` in API 30, and .NET 10 no longer honors it. The modern fix is to listen for **keyboard (IME) insets** on Android and adjust your layout's bottom padding.

**1. Set soft input mode to `AdjustNothing`** so you control the layout yourself:

In `Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs`:
```csharp
[Activity(..., WindowSoftInputMode = SoftInput.AdjustNothing)]
public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity { }
```

**2. Add a behavior that responds to keyboard insets:**

```csharp
#if ANDROID
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using AndroidX.Core.Graphics;
#endif

public static class KeyboardInsetHelper
{
    public static void Register(Page page)
    {
#if ANDROID
        page.HandlerChanged += (s, e) =>
        {
            if (page.Handler?.PlatformView is Android.Views.View view)
            {
                ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(view, new KeyboardInsetsListener(page));
            }
        };
#endif
    }

#if ANDROID
    class KeyboardInsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        readonly Page _page;
        public KeyboardInsetsListener(Page page) => _page = page;

        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Use the larger of keyboard or nav-bar bottom inset
            double bottomPx = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            double bottomDp = bottomPx / v.Resources.DisplayMetrics.Density;

            _page.Padding = new Thickness(0, 0, 0, bottomDp);
            return insets;
        }
    }
#endif
}
```

**3. Wire it up in your chat page:**

```csharp
public partial class ChatPage : ContentPage
{
    public ChatPage()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        KeyboardInsetHelper.Register(this);
    }
}
```

**Why this works:** Instead of relying on the deprecated resize mode, you read the actual IME (keyboard) inset height from Android's `WindowInsetsCompat` API and apply it as bottom padding on your page. When the keyboard opens, the padding pushes your input bar up; when it closes, it resets to the navigation-bar height.

> **Tip:** On iOS this isn't needed — `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` handles it by default in MAUI. The `#if ANDROID` guards keep the behavior platform-specific.
